UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669190044M
AB  - This paper examines the regulatory-approval effect for bidding firms in mutual savings and loan association (MS&L) merger conversions. In a MS&L merger conversion, a mutually-owned thrift converts to stock form of ownership and is simultaneously acquired by an existing or newly formed capital-stock savings and loan. Because the regulatory environment in which capital stock savings and loan associations may acquire MS&Ls introduces uncertainty, it is expected that the abnormal returns surrounding the Office of Thrift Supervision (formerly the Federal Home Loan Bank Board) approval will be positive and significant. This paper finds that the two-day announcement period excess return is negative but not statistically different from zero.
