T1  - The growth of the world's 300 largest banking organizations by country
AU  - G. Goldberg, Lawrence
AU  - Hanweck, Gerald A.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
SP  - 207
EP  - 223
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(91)90047-P
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669190047P
AB  - The size distribution of the largest banks in the world aggregated by country has changed dramatically since 1969 and has aroused both public and academic interest. By examining the distribution of the total assets of the 300 largest banks in the world we document a number of important changes such as the rise of Japanese banks, the decline of American banks, and the cyclical nature of the movement of these shares. Clearly, one of the dominant causes of these changes is fluctuations in exchange rates. We also develop and test a model to explain the growth of large banks by country over one and five year periods by removing the effects of exchange rates. We find that initial deposits are negatively correlated with share of bank assets and that most of the independent economic variables do not explain the growth of large banks by country.
